The article discusses the tragic shooting that took place at a Sikh temple in Oak Creek, Wisconsin in 2012, where a white supremacist killed six people and injured several others. The incident was the deadliest attack on Sikh Americans in the nation's history. The article emphasizes the need to prevent hate crimes and protect places of worship. It highlights the resilience and unity of the Sikh community in the aftermath of the attack, as they cleaned their temple themselves and advocated for the tracking of hate crimes against minority groups. The article calls for action to reduce gun violence, including banning assault weapons and high-capacity magazines, and urges the Senate to follow the House of Representatives in passing relevant legislation.